## Use `System.IO.Abstractions`

The best approach is the established **System.IO.Abstractions** NuGet package — no need to write custom wrappers.

**1. Install:**
```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

**2. Register in DI:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class ConfigService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool FolderExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"ok\":true}") }
});
mockFs.AddDirectory("/data");

var svc = new ConfigService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"ok\":true}", svc.Load("/data/config.json"));
Assert.True(svc.FolderExists("/data"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?**
- Battle-tested, complete API surface (mirrors all of `System.IO`)
- `MockFileSystem` works out of the box — no mocking framework needed
- Only wrap what you use; `IFileSystem.File` and `IFileSystem.Directory` cover your three calls exactly

Once installed, you can migrate call sites one class at a time — add `IFileSystem` as a constructor parameter and replace the static calls with `fileSystem.File.*` / `fileSystem.Directory.*`.
